,"death":{"year":1825,"month":3,"day":7},"parents":{"father_id":"X00078","mother_id":"X01839"},"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"HD0097","children_ids":["HD0102","HD0103","HD0104","HD0105","HD0106","HD0107","HD0108","HD0109","HD0110","HD0111","HD0112","HD0113","HD0114"],"marriage_number":1,"date_year":1775,"date_month":4,"date_day":23}],"sources":[],"gender":"female","tags":[],"number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Ann Woodruff Whittlesey","first_name":"Ann","last_name":"Whittlesey","married_names":["Whittlesey"],"maiden_name":"Woodruff"},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"ann-woodruff-1756"},"HD0097":{"id":"HD0097","has_descendants_documented":true,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"generation_from_thomas":6,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1754,"month":2,"day":24,"city":"Milford","county":"New Haven","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"death":{"year":1835,"month":3,"day":15,"county":"Litchfield","state":"Connecticut"},"parents":{"father_id":"I00020","mother_id":"H00142","mother_research_notes":"Susannah Newton Whittlesey Hamlin (H00142, b. Jan 14, 1716, d. May 10, 1803). Per Whittlesey Genealogy #42 child line: Samuel Whittlesey #42 (I00020) m. Susannah Newton Sept 21, 1743; their fourth child was #135 Roger Newton Whittlesey (HD0097). After Samuel's death in 1768, Susannah remarried Hon. Jabez Hamlin of Middletown — hence her 'Hamlin' display name. STAGE 6Y-11 REVERT NOTE: In Stage 6Y-10 I incorrectly 'fixed' this from H00142 to H00143 (Martha Newton Whittlesey). That was backwards — the two Newton sisters married two Whittlesey brothers: Susannah → Samuel #42, Martha → Chauncey #88. Roger Newton's mother is Susannah, NOT Martha. Reverted in 6Y-11 per book #42 confirmation."},"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"I00075","children_ids":["HD0102","HD0103","HD0104","HD0105","HD0106","HD0107","HD0108","HD0109","HD0110","HD0111","HD0112","HD0113","HD0114"],"marriage_number":1,"date_year":1775,"date_month":4,"date_day":23}],"primary_documents":{"enlistment_record":{"date":"January 21, 1776","text":"Signed \"We, the Subscribers, being convinced of the necessity of a body of forces to defeat certain Wicked Purposes formed by the instruments on Ministerial Tyranny do solemnly engage ourselves and enlist as private soldiers...\" Dated at Litchfield. Signed: ROGER N. WHITTELSEY."}},"tags":["revolutionary_war"],"sources":[{"short":"Whittlesey Genealogy","page":"Entry 135 (full bio + Rev War record)"}],"gender":"male","number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"open_questions":[{"question":"Is Elisha Whittlesey (b. Mar 8, 1783, Southbury CT; d. Jan 7, 1863) a missing child of Roger Newton Whittlesey?","status":"closed","notes":"Elisha Whittlesey (1783-1863) was born in Southbury CT, studied law under Tapping Reeve at Litchfield CT, moved to Canfield, Mahoning County OH in 1806, served as U.S. Congressman from Ohio and comptroller of the U.S. Treasury. His birth year (1783) falls exactly between documented children HD0105 (Chauncey, b.1781) and HD0106 (Susan, b.1784), suggesting he may be a missing child of this entry. Roger Newton Whittlesey (HD0097) lived in Litchfield County CT — where Tapping Reeve's famous law school was located. If confirmed, Elisha is a gen 6 Hooker descendant, and his 20-year law partnership with Eben Newton (HD2927) — also a gen 6 Hooker descendant — becomes a documented civic_peer cross_connection. Action: Check Whittlesey genealogy for Southbury CT branch; Litchfield County records 1783.","resolution":"Elisha Whittlesey (b. Oct 19, 1783 Washington CT) is Whittlesey book entry #310, son of John Whittlesey (#123, b.1741 Newington CT). His line descends from John Whittlesey of Saybrook through Eliphalet→Eliphalet→John→Elisha — a completely different branch from the project's Whittlesey line (which runs through Rev. Samuel Whittlesey of Wallingford/Milford). Elisha is NOT a Hooker descendant."}],"cross_connections":[],"military_service":[{"war":"American Revolutionary War","active_in_war":true,"rank":"Private","dates":"1776","unit":"Col. Andrew Ward Jr.'s Regiment, Capt. Bezaleel Beebe's Company","notes":"Enlisted Jan 21, 1776 at Litchfield for expedition to New York under Gen. Charles Lee. Eight-week term. His musket was appraised as part of the company arms Jan 26, 1776.","war_id":"WAR004"}],"bio":{"display_name":"Roger Newton Whittlesey","first_name":"Roger","last_name":"Whittlesey","middle_name":"Newton","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"military","header":"Eight-week militia tour to defend New York 1776","body":"Roger enlisted at twenty-one in Capt. Bezaleel Beebe's Company under Col. Andrew Ward Jr. and Maj. Gen. Charles Lee in January 1776 — orders reaching Capt. Beebe on a Sunday, the company armed and on the march toward Fairfield by Saturday. The eight-week tour took him to defend New York City, his only documented Revolutionary service."},{"number":2,"category":"career","header":"Justice of the peace, Litchfield County, many years","body":"After the war Roger settled at South Farms in Litchfield County and served as justice of the peace for many years, the position of standing in the rural Connecticut hierarchy. He worked his farm there until his death at eighty-one in March 1835."},{"number":3,"category":"family","header":"Father of thirteen children with Ann Woodruff","body":"Roger married Ann Woodruff of Litchfield in April 1775, the same month as Lexington, and they raised thirteen children together. The youngest, George Washington Whittlesey, was born in 1799 when Roger was forty-five; Ann lived until 1825."}],"slug":"roger-whittlesey-1754"},"HD0102":{"id":"HD0102","has_descendants_documented":false,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"generation_from_thomas":7,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1775,"month":12,"day":18,"city":"South Farms","county":"Litchfield","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"parents":{"father_id":"HD0097","mother_id":"I00075"},"tags":[],"sources":[{"short":"Whittlesey Genealogy","page":"Entry 360"}],"gender":"male","number_of_marriages":1,"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"I00434","date_year":1808,"date_month":11,"date_day":10,"location_state":"Connecticut","location_country":"United States","children_ids":["HD3790","HD3791","HD3792","HD3793","HD3794","HD3795","HD3796"]}],"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"death":{"year":1842,"month":4,"day":15},"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Samuel Whittlesey","first_name":"Samuel","last_name":"Whittlesey","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST120","institution_blurb":"Took charge April 30, 1817 (same day dismissed from New Preston pastorate)."},{"institution_id":"INST002","relationship":"alumnus"}],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"religion","header":"Pastor of New Preston, ten years, 142 added","body":"Samuel was ordained at the First Church of New Preston Conn. on December 30, 1807 and served until his dismissal April 30, 1817. Over those ten years 142 members joined the church and 167 were baptized."},{"number":2,"category":"career","header":"Took charge of Hartford's Deaf and Dumb Asylum","body":"On the same day he was dismissed from his New Preston pastorate, April 30, 1817, Samuel took charge of the American Asylum for the Deaf and Dumb at Hartford Connecticut. The asylum had opened only weeks earlier as the first permanent school for the deaf in the United States, founded by Thomas Hopkins Gallaudet."},{"number":3,"category":"education","header":"Yale College 1803, Phi Beta Kappa with Master's","body":"Samuel graduated Yale College in 1803 with Phi Beta Kappa honors and an A.M. He was licensed to preach the following June 1804, three years before his New Preston ordination."},{"number":4,"category":"career","header":"Conducted seminaries at Utica and Canandaigua New York","body":"After his Hartford Asylum tenure, Samuel and his wife Abigail Goodrich conducted 'large seminaries' at Utica and Canandaigua New York. While in Utica in 1832 Abigail began publishing The Mother's Magazine, the early American periodical of maternal Christian instruction she would edit for nearly two decades."}],"education":[{"institution":"Yale College","institution_id":"INST002","graduation_year":1803,"degree":"B.A.","honors":"Phi Beta Kappa; A.M."}],"slug":"samuel-whittlesey-1775"},"HD0103":{"id":"HD0103","has_descendants_documented":false,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"generation_from_thomas":7,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1777,"month":10,"day":31},"parents":{"father_id":"HD0097","mother_id":"I00075"},"tags":[],"sources":[],"gender":"male","number_of_marriages":2,"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"I00435","date_year":1800,"date_month":7,"date_day":4,"location_state":"Connecticut","location_country":"United States","end_type":"death_of_spouse","end_year":1818,"children_ids":["HD3833","HD3834","HD3835","HD3836"]},{"marriage_number":2,"spouse_id":"I00436","d